metadata.name: Modern Times #122
metadata.description:
Created by Eko33, a generative artist featured at the Tezos Ecosystem Exhibition (Art Basel Miami 2021).

This generative artwork creates a limited series of distinctive artworks based on unique hash seeds.

The algorithmic approach of this collection generates a broad spectrum of unique outcomes, inspired by the "giant machine" from the movie "Modern Times."

Beyond a classic mechanical representation, Eko33 aims to convey multiple emotions while embracing the cold nature of algorithms.

Computer-generated generative art can be seen as a gigantic assembly line. Still, its true nature gives the artist complete freedom from all commercially available tools/constraints.

The collection "Modern Times" highlights the dark ages of generative arts using a bichromatic color palette and evolves toward the contemporary "Digital Renaissance" era using warmer, more acid and "pop" colors.

About Eko33:
Official fx(hash) page: https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Eko33
Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/

metadata.name: reborn #154
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamo≈õƒá are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: kaonashi #7
metadata.description:
Reviewing Memories: Kaonashi, the Wandering Spirit in a Ruined City

In my recollections, Kaonashi is a wandering spirit in a desolate, ruined city. The memories are filled with vivid images and emotions. Kaonashi, draped in tattered garments, roams the empty streets and abandoned structures. The city, ravaged by time, serves as a haunting backdrop. Nature reclaims the urban landscape, adding to the eerie ambiance. Kaonashi's faceless presence exudes sorrow and longing.

metadata.name: Pumpkin Head #41
metadata.description: The creatures observed within the desolate cemetery of the city are commonly known as "pumpkin heads." According to local accounts, these entities are believed to be the most horrifying creatures in the entire city, instilling sheer terror in those who encounter them. It is rumored that the mere sound of their voices has the power to awaken the dormant zombies, causing them to rise from their graves once again.

metadata.name: terrains #228
metadata.description:
A generative set of imaginary landscapes.

Terrains continues a study of topographic media translations that began with Plastic Landscapes (2016) and our Field Guide to Martian Landscapes (2017). While the Field Guide focused on analyzing topographies of another planet, interpreted through telescopic imaging and software translation, this project focuses on the procedural generation of nonexistent landscapes. These landscapes are generated through a complex manipulation of perlin noise, a recurring algorithm used in videogames, film VFX, and generative art since the 1980s that resembles natural geological formations. By no means new, this tradition is part of a lineage of digital visualization projects focused on reproducing nature through algorithmic means. Our algorithm generates sequential bands of noise mapped on an X-Y plane, rendered in an oblique architectural projection, a techniques that comes from technical drawing conventions. This perspective produces a layering effect that flattens the terrain in an architectural way. Neither realistic nor completely abstract, the system plays with projection, entropy, and constraints to produce a collection of imaginary terrains sited on the Tezos blockchain.

We must also credit all who have explored this field of work: Ken Perlin, James M. Bardeen, Stephen Schmitt, Paul Bourke, Joseph Claghorn, Amit Patel, Inigo Quilez, Matt DesLauriers, and many many more...

Press "s" to download PNG.
Press "r" to redraw and shift stripes.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2023

metadata.name: Vezels #12
metadata.description:
Vezels is a generative art algorithm that explores realistic color mixing. In this project, the canvas is treated as a wet painting where each new paint layer brings forth new colors. The algorithm starts with a color palette of three hues, along with black and white. It then creates overlapping and intertwining shapes, offering opportunities for new color blends. The output reminded me of the threads of a rope, either coming together or unraveling. Hence the name ‚ÄòVezels‚Äô, the Dutch word for ‚ÄòFibers‚Äô.

I used the 'spectral.js' library to create realistic color mixing, which I combined with a shader to improve performance. As a way of showing gratitude, 10% percent of the proceeds from each minted edition on primary will go to Ronald van Wijnen, the creator of 'spectral.js'

**Exporting**
You can add ‚Äò&resolution=[integer]‚Äô to the url to obtain a higher resolution render. You can go up to 6 times the original size, depending on your device. Press ‚Äòs‚Äô to save it to a .png.

metadata.name: Bento Boxes #255
metadata.description:
Everybody needs a bento box in the cryptowinter.
The project calls for an adopted nostalgia of little kids that has been handed bento box by their parents before school‚Äî a little moment of protected comfort before heading out for an adventure.

‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢

The first collaboration project of MEK.txt and IceRain in FXHash. A work based on MEK.txt‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Bento Boxes‚Äù and IceRain‚Äôs excellent codes, Bento Boxes aims to be a fun visual and code exploration project on the generative art corridor. Pure code, no libraries.

Bento Boxes deconstructed the visual system on MEK.txt's artwork, titled almost similarly, ‚ÄúThe Bento Boxes‚Äù. Rebuilt it from scratch with codes, adding variants of colours and shapes‚Äî without losing the strong characteristics of the base artwork.

metadata.name: tr4ns4ctions #61
metadata.description:
Tr4ns4ctions is a series of real-time animations that use pixels to create an abstraction of the movement of values. The pixels are constantly rearranging, being transferred from offer to taker, liquify, appear and disappear. They are forming endless compositions, sometimes intransparent or with strange spins.

The level of abstraction has been set to a 2x pixel size and the color palette of the NES with 12 different color modes. 16 pixel patterns serve as the fundamental building blocks and a simplex noise field determines the direction of movement.

click || space => pause/unpause

View all tr4ns4ctions at https://tr4ns4ctions.com

Kim Asendorf, 2022
